    "b-chrome-decision-standalone-4": {
      "id": "b-chrome-decision-standalone-4",
      "flavour": "decision",
      "props": {
        "status": "accepted",
        "title": "Build chrome standalone and unwired, then wire it in a later pass"
      },
      "text": [
        {
          "insert": "Every component under "
        },
        {
          "insert": "src/chrome/",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true,
            "reference": {
              "kind": "source",
              "path": "packages/canvas/src/chrome"
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": " was built with zero imports from the live editor — no "
        },
        {
          "insert": "CanvasStage.tsx",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": ", "
        },
        {
          "insert": "InteractiveCanvasEditor.tsx",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": ", "
        },
        {
          "insert": "actions.ts",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": ", or "
        },
        {
          "insert": "interaction.ts",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": " — and zero edits to those files. This was deliberate: it let the chrome surface be developed, styled, and pixel-matched against FigJam reference recordings entirely on its own, in parallel with unrelated model and interaction work, and wired into the live editor only in a later pass (W3-wire) once the visual layer was settled. Two concrete benefits follow from the isolation: the UI work is parallelizable against other tracks touching the editor internals, and each component's test can assert measured geometry (stadium radius, colors, button counts, group/divider structure) against plain props in jsdom, with no dependency on canvas interaction state, model wiring, or a running editor instance."
        }
      ],
      "children": []
    },
